## Architecture Rules
- All SDK interactions go through adapters in src/quad/adapters/
- Never import SDK modules (qnn, snpe, hexagon) directly in tool handlers
- All tool inputs/outputs use Pydantic models from src/quad/models/
- MockAdapter must be updated whenever any adapter interface changes
- Platform-specific logic lives in src/quad/platforms/ — tools are platform-agnostic
- Code generation uses Jinja2 templates from templates/ — no inline string building

## Code Style
- Use async/await for all I/O operations (SDK calls, file ops, network)
- Type hints required on all public functions (mypy --strict compatible)
- Structured logging via structlog — no print() or logging.getLogger()
- Error handling: raise QUADError subclasses, never bare Exception
- Config values from quad.toml via ServerConfig — no hardcoded paths or constants

## Testing
- Every new tool/adapter method needs a corresponding unit test
- Mock mode must work without any SDK installed
- Use pytest fixtures from conftest.py for common setup
- Tests must pass with `adapter_mode = "mock"` in CI

## Patterns
- Adapter pattern: SDKAdapter ABC → concrete adapters (QNN, SNPE, Mock)
- Factory pattern: AdapterFactory selects adapter based on config
- Template method: tools follow detect → validate → execute → format → respond
- Pydantic for all boundaries: config parsing, API input, API output

## Do NOT
- Import QNN/SNPE/Hexagon modules at module level (breaks mock mode)
- Use subprocess with shell=True (command injection risk)
- Hardcode SDK paths (use config system)
- Skip input validation (Pydantic handles it at tool boundaries)
- Add SDK binaries or model files to git
